40","after 1561":"na 1561","Aft. 1570":"na 1570","1549":"1549","Marlborough, Wiltshire, England":"Marlborough, Wiltshire, England","Hannington, Wiltshire, England":"Hannington, Wiltshire, England","All Canning, Wiltshire, England":"All Cannings, Wiltshire, England","Marlborough, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Marlborough, Wiltshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kennett, Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1540–abt 1590":"1540–about 1590","1540–1590":"1540–1590","1540–1570":"1540–1570","1565–1590":"1565–1590","1520–1561":"1520–1561","1520–Female":"1520–Deceased","abt 1590":"about 1590","1561":"1561","1571":"1571","1570":"1570","1590":"1590","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1565":"1565","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","1585":"1585","1540":"1540","after 1561":"after 1561","Aft. 1570":"after 1570","1549":"1549","Marlborough, Wiltshire, England":"Marlborough, Wiltshire, England","Hannington, Wiltshire, England":"Hannington, Wiltshire, England","All Canning, Wiltshire, England":"All Cannings, Wiltshire, England","Marlborough, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Marlborough, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Kennett, Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Masselin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Lucien, Germain, Jacques, Normand, Amedee, Fernand, Gilles, Laurent, Alphee, Benoit.","French: from an Old French personal name, a pet form of <i>Asse</i>; see   Ace   1. Compare   Ashline  .","Altered form of French   Ancelin  . Compare   Ashland   3,   Ashley   2, and   Aslin   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Ace","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from Old French <i>Ace</i>, <i>Asse</i>, or <i>Asce</i>, all from the ancient Germanic male personal name <i>Az(z)o</i>, <i>Atso</i>, <i>Adso</i>, or possibly the female personal name <i>Aza</i>. These were pet forms of ancient Germanic compound names formed with <i>adal-</i> ‘noble’, such as <i>Adalbert</i> (later   Albert  ) and <i>Adalheidis</i> (later <i>Alice</i>; see   Allis  )."]},{"name":"Ashline","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Asselin   1.","History: Bearers of the surname <i>Ashline</i> are descendants of one or another of the brothers Jacques and David Asselin from France (see   Asselin  )."]},{"name":"Aslin","meanings":["English: from the Middle English male personal name <i>Asselyn</i> (from Old French <i>Acelin</i>, <i>Ascelin</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Azilin</i>). There was also a feminine form, <i>A(s)celine</i>.","Altered form of   Asselin   2, a surname of French origin.","Swedish (<b>Åslin</b>): topographic or ornamental name from <i>ås</i> ‘ridge’ + the suffix <i>-lin</i>, derived from Latin <i>-(l)inius</i> ‘relating to’. Compare   Ashlin   and   Oslin  ."]},{"name":"Ashley","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places (especially in southern and central England) named Ashley, from Old English <i>æsc</i> ‘ash’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","Americanized form of French Canadian   Asselin   2.","In some cases also an Americanized form of German   Eschler  ."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":9,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":18,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":29,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":31,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":45,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":47,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry Masselin was born in 1540, in All Cannings, Wiltshire, England, his father, Charles Masselin Maslyn Maslinge, was 21 and his mother, Martha, was 20. He had at least 1 daughter with Ann Edwarde. He died about 1590, in Marlborough, Wiltshire, England, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1540–abt 1590":"1540–umbes 1590","1540–1590":"1540–1590","1540–1570":"1540–1570","1565–1590":"1565–1590","1520–1561":"1520–1561","1520–Female":"1520–Surnud","abt 1590":"umbes 1590","1561":"1561","1571":"1571","1570":"1570","1590":"1590","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1565":"1565","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","1585":"1585","1540":"1540","after 1561":"pärast 1561","Aft. 1570":"pärast 1570","1549":"1549","Marlborough, Wiltshire, England":"Marlborough, Wiltshire, England","Hannington, Wiltshire, England":"Hannington, Wiltshire, England","All Canning, Wiltshire, England":"All Cannings, Wiltshire, England","Marlborough, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Marlborough, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kennett, Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1540–abt 1590":"1540–noin 1590","1540–1590":"1540–1590","1540–1570":"1540–1570","1565–1590":"1565–1590","1520–1561":"1520–1561","1520–Female":"1520–Kuollut","abt 1590":"noin 1590","1561":"1561","1571":"1571","1570":"1570","1590":"1590","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1565":"1565","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","1585":"1585","1540":"1540","after 1561":"1561 jälkeen","Aft. 1570":"1570 jälkeen","1549":"1549","Marlborough, Wiltshire, England":"Marlborough, Wiltshire, England","Hannington, Wiltshire, England":"Hannington, Wiltshire, England","All Canning, Wiltshire, England":"All Cannings, Wiltshire, England","Marlborough, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Marlborough, Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kennett, Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"f